- We have

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n-1)^3 &= (2n)^3 - 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) - 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
  &= 8n^3 - 12n^2 + 6n - 1\end{aligned}
  $$

  and

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n+1)^3 &= (2n)^3 + 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) + 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
  &= 8n^3 + 12n^2 + 6n + 1\end{aligned}
  $$

  Summing our expressions for $(2n-1)^3$ and $(2n+1)^3$, we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 8n^3 - \cancel{12n^2} + 6n - \cancel{1} + 8n^3 + \cancel{12n^2} + 6n + \cancel{1}
  \end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \answer{(2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 = 16n^3 + 12n} \hspace{2em}\end{aligned}
  $$

- Let $2n-1$ and $2n+1$ be two consecutive odd integers for some
$n \in \mathbb{Z}$.
  The sum of the cubes of $2n-1$ and $2n+1$ is

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{6.4em} (2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 16n^3 + 12n \hspace{2em} [\text{by part (a)}] \\[6pt]
  &= 4n(4n^2 + 3) \hspace{2.22em} [\text{multiple of $4$}]\end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence the sum of the cubes of any two consecutive odd integers is
divisible by four.

