(2k+1)^3-36(2k+1)^2-432&= 0
\end{align*}
$$

Consider the term $36(2k+1)^2$, we can rewrite this as $2\times18(2k+1)^2$, therefore this term is even.
Hence we can write $36(2k+1)^2$ as $2a$, where $a \in 	\mathbb{Z}$.

$$
\begin{align*}
    \textcolor{white}{hack}\tag*{\textbf{R1}}
\end{align*}
$$

The term $-432$ is also even.
Let's expand the first term

$$
\begin{align*}
(2k+1)^3&=8k^3+12k^2+6k+1\\[6pt]
&=2(4k^3+6k^2+3k)+1\\[6pt]
&=2b+1 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Where $b \in 	\mathbb{Z}$.
Therefore the original simplified equation can be written in the following form

$$
\begin{align*}
0&= 2b+1-2a-432\\[6pt]
0&=2(b-a-216)+1
\end{align*}    
$$

Let $c=b-a-216$ where where $c \in 	\mathbb{Z}$. Hence

$$
\begin{align*}
0&= 2c+1 \tag*{\textbf{R1}}
\end{align*}   
$$

This is a contradiction as $0$ is an even number and $2c+1$ is odd.

