- The diagram below shows a region bound by $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ and the points $E(a, f(a))$ and $F(a+2, f(a+2)))$.
  The function $f$ needs to be used to calculate the $y-$coordinate values of $E$ and $F$.
  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/41d8354f-4cec-4922-8437-0ca160d21c7a/images/7597d9d0-8ed4-4fea-8e36-94f1a14efc4c/AA1290-a4.JPEG)


  To find the area we need to find the linear function $g(x)$ in terms of $a$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  $\mathrm{g}(x)$ is of the form $g(x)=m_gx+c_g$.
  Where the gradient, $m_g$, is

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      m_g&=\dfrac{y_2+y_1}{x_2-x_1}\\[3pt]
      &=\dfrac{\mathrm{f}(a+2)-\mathrm{f}(a)}{a+2-a}\\[3pt]
      &=\dfrac{(3-a^2)-(3-(a-2)^2))}{2}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Simplifying we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\dfrac{-a^2+(a-2)^2}{2}\\[3pt]
      &=\dfrac{-a^2+a^2-4a+4}{2}\\[3pt]
      m_g&=2-2a \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[3pt]    
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  Using the point $A(a, f(a))$ we can find the $y-$intercept, $c_g$, of $g(x)$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      y&=(2-2a)x+c_g\\[3pt]
      \mathrm{f}(a)&=(2-2a)a+c_g\\[3pt]
      3-(a-2)^2&=(2-2a)a+c_g\\[3pt]    
      c_g&=3-(a-2)^2-2a+2a^2\\[3pt]    
      c_g&=a^2+2a-1 \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[3pt] 
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  The function $g(x)$ in terms of $a$ is

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \mathrm{g}(x)=(2-2a)x+a^2+2a-1
  \end{align*}
  $$

  The shaded area is given by the following definite integral

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\int_{E_x}^{F_x} (f(x)-g(x)) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (4x-x^2-1-((2-2a)x+a^2+2a-1)) \,dx \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Simplifying we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (4x-x^2-1-(2x-2ax+a^2+2a-1)) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (2x-x^2+2ax-a^2-2a) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (-x^2+(2a+2)x-a^2-2a) \,dx
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now we can integrate each term, using the inverse power rule, and substitute in the limits.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =\left[-\dfrac{1}{3}x^3+\dfrac{2a+2}{2}x^2-x(a^2+2a)\right]_{a}^{a+2}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =-\dfrac{1}{3}(a+2)^3+(a+1)(a+2)^2-(a+2)(a^2+2a)-...\\
  ...\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3+(a+1)a^2-a(a^2+2a)\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Expanding and simplifying we gradient

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =-\dfrac{1}{3}(a^3+6a^2+12a+8)+a^3+5a^2+8a+4-(a^3+4a^2+4a)-...\\
  ...\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3+a^3+a^2-a^3-2a^2\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We continue to collect any like terms and simplify to get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =\cancel{-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3}-2a^2-4a-\dfrac{8}{3}+a^2+4a+4-...\\
  ...\left(\cancel{-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3}-a^2\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=\cancel{-2a^2}-\cancel{4a}-\dfrac{8}{3}+\cancel{a^2}+\cancel{4a}+4+\cancel{a^2}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\
  &=-\dfrac{8}{3}+4\\
  &=\answer{\dfrac{4}{3} \,\text{units}^2}\hspace{3em}\text{...as required}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We start by showing the base case is true.
  This is when $n=1$.
  Let's first consider the value of the L.H.S. of the proposition

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2^1\times \cos{2^{1-1}x}&=\textcolor{red}{2\cos{x}}
  \end{align*}  
  $$

  And the value of the R.H.S. is

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \frac{\sin{2^1x}}{\sin{x}}&=\frac{2\sin{x}\cos{x}}{\sin{x}}\\[6pt]
  &=\textcolor{red}{2\cos{x}}\\[6pt]
  &=\text{L.H.S.}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{R1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence we have shown the proposition is true when $n=1$.
  The next step is to assume the proposition is true when $n=k$ where $k \in \mathbb{Z^+}$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2^k\times \cos{x} \times \cos{2x} \times \cos{4x} \times ... \times \cos{2^{k-1}x}&=\frac{\sin{2^kx}}{\sin{x}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Next we need to use the assumption to show that the proposition is true  when $n=k+1$.
  Hence we need to prove

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2^{k+1}\times \cos{x} \times \cos{2x} \times \cos{4x} \times ... \times \cos{2^{k}x}&=\frac{\sin{2^{k+1}x}}{\sin{x}}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Let's start by rewriting the L.H.S. so it looks similar to the L.H.S. of the assumption

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \text{L.H.S.}&=2\,\textcolor{blue}{\times2^{k}\times \cos{x} \times \cos{2x} \times \cos{4x} \times ... \times \cos{2^{k-1}x}}\times\cos{2^{k}x}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Notice the blue part is now the same as the L.H.S. of the assumption, hence we can replace it with the R.H.S. of the assumption

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=2\left(\textcolor{blue}{\frac{\sin2^kx}{\sin{x}}}\right)\times\cos{2^{k}x}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This is known as the inductive step.
  We can rearrange the trigonometric identity $\sin{2\theta}=2\sin{\theta}\cos{\theta}$ to

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \sin{\theta}\cos{\theta}&=\tfrac{1}{2}\sin{2\theta}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  and use it to rewrite our L.H.S. giving

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=2 \times \frac{\sin2^kx}{\sin{x}}\times\cos{2^{k}x}\\[12pt]
      &=2\times \frac{\tfrac{1}{2}\sin{(2\times2^kx})}{\sin{x}}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[12pt]
      &=\frac{\sin{(2\times2^kx})}{\sin{x}}\\[12pt]
      &=\answer{\dfrac{\sin{2^{k+1}x}}{\sin{x}}}\hspace{0.525em}\text{...as required.}\\[12pt]
      &=\text{R.H.S.}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We have shown the proposition is true when $n=1$ and we have shown it to be true when $n=k+1$, assuming $n=k$ is true. Therefore by the principle of mathematical induction the proposition is true for all positive integer values of $n$.
- 
  - We begin by noting that $\sin{8x}$ is a composite function.
    Hence we can use the formula for the Macluarin series for sine but replace $x$ with $8x$.

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \sin{x}&=x-\frac{x^3}{3!}+\frac{x^5}{5!}-...\\[6pt]
        \sin{8x}&=8x-\frac{(8x)^3}{3!}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    We only need the first two non-zero terms hence we get

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        &=8x-\frac{512x^3}{6}\\[6pt]
        &=\answer{8x-\dfrac{256}{3}x^3}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

  - Let's begin by using a general power series to represent the result of the quotient

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \frac{\sin{8x}}{\sin{x}}&=a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2+a_3x^3+...
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Where $a_i$ are real numbers we must determine.
    We can use the result from part (a) and the general formula for sine to write the numerator and denominator as a Maclaurin series up to the $x^3$ term

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \frac{8x-\frac{256}{3}x^3}{x-\frac{x^3}{3!}}&=a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2+a_3x^3+...
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Recall, we only need the first two non-zero terms which will mean up to and including the $x^3$ term.
    It can be challenging to attempt to use long division to rewrite the L.H.S. Often a better strategy, when facing problems like this, is to rewrite the division as a multiplication

    $$
    \begin{align*}
            8x-\frac{256}{3}x^3&=\left(x-\frac{x^3}{3!}\right)\left(a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2+a_3x^3+...\right)\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    We can now expand the R.H.S. until we have all of the terms required to give the $x$ and $x^3$ terms.

    $$
    \begin{align*}
            8x-\frac{256}{3}x^3&=a_0x-\frac{a_0x^3}{6}+\cancel{a_1x^2}-\cancel{\frac{a_1x^4}{6}}+a_2x^3-\cancel{\frac{a_2x^5}{6}}\\[6pt]
            &=a_0x-\frac{a_0x^3}{6}++a_2x^3\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}   
    $$

    There is no $x^2$ term therefore $a_1$ must be zero. Also we don't need any power of $x$ higher than $3$. So we can cancel out another two terms.
    We can now equate the coefficients of the $x-$terms on the left and right side giving

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        8&=a_0\hspace{6em}\text{for $x$}\\[6pt]
        -\frac{256}{3}&=-\frac{a_0}{6}+a_2\hspace{3em}\text{for $x^3$}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    We can see that $a_0=8$ hence we can use this to find $a_2$

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        -\frac{256}{3}&=-\frac{8}{6}+a_2\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}\\[6pt]
        &=-\frac{8}{6}+\frac{6a_2}{6}\\[6pt]
        -512&=-8+6a_2\\[6pt]
        6a_2&=-504\\[6pt]
        a_2&=-84\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}   
    $$

    Therefore, referring back to the series expansion at the start of the solution, we can see that the first two non-zero terms are

    $$
    \begin{align*}
    \frac{\sin{8x}}{\sin{x}}&=a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2+a_3x^3+...\\[6pt]
    &=\answer{8-84x^2}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

  - The integral given is a very difficult integral to perform directly.
    However, notice that it is of the form of the proposition from part (a).
    If we take the proposition and let $n=3$ we get

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        2^3\times \cos{x} \times \cos{2x} \times \cos{4x} &=\frac{\sin{2^3x}}{\sin{x}}\\[6pt]
        \cos{x} \times \cos{2x} \times \cos{4x}&=\frac{\sin{8x}}{8\sin{x}}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(A1)}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Hence we can rewrite the integral as

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \int_{0}^{0.1}\cos{x}\cos{2x}\cos{4x}\,\mathrm{d}x&=\int_{0}^{0.1}\frac{\sin{8x}}{8\sin{x}}\,\mathrm{d}x\\[6pt]
        &=\tfrac{1}{8}\int_{0}^{0.1}\frac{\sin{8x}}{\sin{x}}\,\mathrm{d}x\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(A1)}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    The result is still a difficult integral to perform but the key word in the question is estimate. This suggests we should use the series expansion from part (b)(ii).
    Hence we get

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \int_{0}^{0.1}\cos{x}\cos{2x}\cos{4x}\,\mathrm{d}x&\approx \tfrac{1}{8} \int_{0}^{0.1}\left(8-84x^2\right)\,\mathrm{d}x
    \end{align*}  
    $$

    Integrating each term we get

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        &=\tfrac{1}{8}\bigg[8x-28x^3\bigg]_{0}^{0.1}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*} 
    $$

    Substituting in the limits we get

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        &=\tfrac{1}{8}\left(8(0.1)-28(0.1)^3\right)\\[6pt]
        &=0.1-3.5\times0.001\\[6pt]
        &=0.1-0.0035\\[6pt]
        &=\answer{0.0965}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$
